<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-643-568  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 643 568.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computergram International  July 18 1990 n1470* Full Text COPYRIGHT Apt Data Services (England) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Network Computing Devices sets new low in X-terminal tags. (NCD19bcomputer sells for $2,300) (product announcement)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Network Computing Devices Inc. (product introduction).andO;Product:   Network Computing Devices NCD19b (Graphics system) (productintroduction).andO;Topic:     MarketingX TerminalsPricing PolicyX Windows (Standard)TerminalsProduct Introduction.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>NETWORK COMPUTING DEVICES SETS NEW LOW IN X-TERMINAL TAGSandM;Network Computing Devices Inc has the dedicated X Window System terminalmarket to itself for a desperately short time, but the company is doing allit can to hold onto its lead, and this week claimed price leadership in the19&quot; X terminal market with the $2,300 NCD19b, which uses a new gate array toreplace some 40 parts around the 16MHz 68000 processor to cut the cost, anduses a lower resolution screen, 1,024 by 800 pixels rather than the 1,280 by1,024 of the NCD19.andP;  Over the next year, the firm plans to add further modelsof the entry-level family.andP;  The Mountain View, California company reckonsthat its new model is cheap enough to start replacing ASCII and 3270terminals for transaction processing and general purpose office automationapplications where windowing is desirable but ultra-high resolution is notessential.andP;  It can simultaneously access Unix and DEC VMS kit from differentwindows, and supports two-dimensional graphics as well as text and windows.andO;It comes with 2Mb expandable to 5Mb and is &quot;up to three times faster thanDEC's VT1000&quot;.andO;</TEXT></DOC>